          "body": "The idol section (vv. 15-18) is one of the Old Testament's sharpest concentrated polemics against idolatry, nearly identical to Psalm 115:4-8 — likely a liturgical refrain used in Second Temple worship. The psalmist's strategy is anatomical: he lists every faculty the idols appear to possess (mouth, eyes, ears, breath) and immediately negates each one. The structure is deliberately frustrating — it raises expectation and dashes it four times in succession. The climax comes in verse 18: 'Those who make them will be like them, yes, everyone who trusts in them.' This is the psalm's most searching pastoral claim. Worship is not neutral. Whatever you give your trust to will form you into its image — a principle Jonathan Edwards developed theologically in the Affections: the dominant object of a person's delight and trust shapes the moral and spiritual architecture of the soul. The idol-maker becomes mute, blind, deaf. The Yahweh-worshiper, by contrast, is called to bless — to speak — in the very next verse (v. 19). The contrast is the invitation: do not be silenced by your gods. Bless the LORD who breathes life and hears prayer."
